We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

GSO to consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant and conduct semestral physical count of inventories and submit the RPCI; 

Municipal Accountant to record supplies as expense upon actual consumption based on the SSMI or upon issuance to the intended recipients using the proforma journal entries below:

We recommended and the Sanggunig Bayan agreed to:
6.6.1 	stop the practice of enacting a supplemental budget for expenditures under the Trust Fund as the accounts under said fund have specific purposes which shall be used only for the purposes for which the funds were created or received;
6.6.2 	issue an SB Resolution, instead of an appropriation ordinance if within the 5-year period for a change of expenditure item funded from the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to Trust Fund.

We recommended that the management:

require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
require the inventory committee to conduct physical count of all its local road network system and prepare the Report on the physical Count of Road Network System;
require the GSO to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete record for all roads and its component;

require the Municipal Accountant to support with the required records and reports the Road Networks recorded back in the books amounting to P11,730,856.02 and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the Local Road Network System of the municipality.

In order to correct the aforementioned  deficiencies, we  recommended that the:
2.8.1 Sangguniang Bayan
revisit the provisions of  Municipal Ordinance No. 135-2016 or the Traffic and Order Code of Lidlidda, Ilocos Sur  and consider the deletion of  phrase in Section 1 of Article V which gives the PNP the authority to collect payments from traffic and order code violators  because this provision is contrary to basic accounting and auditing rules and regulations as well as  basic internal control principles, and
henceforth  consider existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations and basic internal control principles in formulating future municipal ordinances;
2.8.2 	Municipal Mayor
require the PNP to stop accepting payments of penalties from traffic violators but instead issue only the original copy of the Traffic Citation Tickets to traffic violators and instruct them to pay at the MTO;
require the Municipal Treasurer to collect the whole amount of penalty indicated in the Traffic Citation Ticket and  issue  official receipt for every collection, indicate in the OR   the Traffic Citation number pertaining to such collection as ready reference, and give the original copy of the OR to the payor;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to release the 50% share of the PNP  in the collection of penalties from traffic violators through the issuance of official receipt by the latter acknowledging such remittance.

We recommended that Management:
3.6.1 propose a supplemental budget for the payment of terminal leave benefits for the five separated employees/officials ;
require the Municipal Budget Officer to obligate the appropriated amount based on the approved supplemental budget;
require the Municipal Accountant  to immediately  recognize a payable account while waiting for the decision of the appeal.

5.4 	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
5.4.1 	submit justification/explanation on the aforementioned lapses;
5.4.2 	require all the collectors that at the close of each business day, they accomplish all the data in the RCD, affix their signatures therein and turn over all their collections to her;
5.4.3 	verify the correctness of all entries in the RCD prepared by every collector  and afterwhich, affix her signature therein, and
5.4.4 	instruct all the collectors to always fill out all the data in the official receipt before issuing the same to the payor and see to it that the date of the RCD tallies with the date of the official receipts issued.

11.9.1 	require the Municipal Accountant to prepare periodic financial statements and reports on the operations of the Poultry Layer Production to serve as guide in making economic decisions;
11.9.2 	instruct the Finance Committee to revisit the 5 -year  business plan and evaluate the existing internal controls in place and  recommend corrective measures whenever necessary;
11.9.3 	require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer  to see to it that all sales of eggs, culled layers, feed bags and manure are duly accounted for and that all disbursements pertaining to this business endeavor are reasonable particularly the consumption of feeds and medicines by the pullets, and
11.9.4 	consider the discontinuance of operations of the Poultry Layer Production if net losses continue to be incurred.

We recommended that the management:

Require the Inventory committee to conduct the required annual physical count of the PPE as of December 31 of every year.  The actual count may be undertaken any month during the current year, but has to be updated at year-end.
Require all Department Heads to advise their Staffs to cooperate with the Inventory Committee to ensure the success of the conduct of the physical count;

Invite a representative of the Auditor to witness the inventory taking;

Require the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the RPCPPE and Accounting records after the physical count, investigate discrepancies, if any, and effect the necessary adjustments;
Require the GSO-Designate/Property Unit to submit a copy of the RPCPPE to the COA office not later than January 31 of the succeeding year;

Require the GSO-Designate/Property Unit to maintain complete, accurate and updated PCs; post property tag/number on the prominent portion of every movable non-expendable property/equipment; and dispose of the unserviceable property.

